# Bandit Level 2 → Level 3

## Objective
The goal of this level was to find the password for the next level.  
The password was stored in a file called `--spaces in this filename--` located in the home directory.

---

## Challenge
This level involved working with a filename that contained spaces.  
I did not find this level too difficult because I already had some experience working with files that contain spaces in Linux.

I understood that spaces in filenames need to be handled carefully so Linux reads the whole filename as one string.

---

## Steps I Took

First, I moved to the home directory:

cd ~

Then I listed the files to confirm the file existed:

ls

To read the contents of the file, I used:

cat ./"--spaces in this filename--"

This command successfully displayed the password for the next level.

I used quotation marks so Linux would treat the entire filename as one piece of text instead of separating the words by spaces.

---

## Password for Level 3
MNk8KNH3Usiio41PRUEoDFPqfxLPlSmx

---

## Commands Learned

### cd ~
The `cd` command changes directories.  
`cd ~` moves to the user's home directory.

### ls
The `ls` command lists files and directories in the current location.

### cat
The `cat` command displays the contents of a file.

### "./filename"
Quotation marks are used when filenames contain spaces.  
This allows Linux to read the entire filename correctly as one string.
